T(v)=s_{1}\langle  v,e_{1}\rangle  f_{1}+…+s_{m}\langle  v,e_{m}\rangle  f_{m}
for each v\in  V.

There are times when the notation for Finite sets is clunky or impractical (e.g., write out the first 10^{120} prime numbers). We have another notation for describing a set: if P[x] is a unary predicate and X is a set, then we write
\{x\in  X\mid  P[x]\}
which describes "The set of x\in  X such that P[x] holds". The vertical bar ("|") is read "such that". The allowable predicates P[-] must form a valid sentence. (This form of set builder notation is called "the axiom scheme of specification" in ZFC set theory.)

The other form of set builder notation which appears frequently: if F(-) is some construction, and P[-] is a unary predicate, and X is a set, then
\{F(x)\mid  x\in  X,P[x]\}
describes the set obtained by applying F to each element of X which satisfies the predicate P.

