Then f is a bijection.

Let E_{n} be a countable collection of countably infinite sets. Then
S=\bigcup ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}
is countably infinite.

For each n\in \mathbb {N}, let us form a sequence (x_{n,k}) of elements of E_{n}. Then we arrange these sequences into an infinite table
\begin {matrix} x_{1,1} & x_{1,2} & x_{1,3} & x_{1,4} & \ldots \\ x_{2,1} & x_{2,2} & x_{2,3} & x_{2,4} & \ldots \\ x_{3,1} & x_{3,2} & x_{3,3} & x_{3,4} & \ldots \\ x_{4,1} & x_{4,2} & x_{4,3} & x_{4,4} & \ldots \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  \end {matrix}
Then we form a sequence by ordering the table as x_{1,1}, x_{2,1}, x_{1,2}, x_{3,1}, x_{2,2}, x_{1,3}, x_{4,1}, x_{3,2}, x_{2,3}, x_{1,4}, …, where we remove duplicate entries as they are encountered. This gives us a countably infinite sequence of S.

We form the countably infinite family E_{n}=\{z/n\in \mathbb {Q}\mid  z\in \mathbb {Z},\gcd (z,n)=1\} where n\in \mathbb {N} is a positive integer. Each member is bijective with the integers, which is countably infinite. Then
S=\bigcup ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}
is countably infinite by Cantor's diagonal argument, and S bijective to the set \mathbb {Q}. Hence \mathbb {Q} is countably infinite.

